InVivoStat Repeated Measures Parametric Analysis

Response and covariance structure

The Resp8 response is currently being analysed by the Repeated Measures Parametric Analysis module.

The response has been square root transformed prior to analysis.

The repeated measures mixed model analysis is using the unstructured covariance structure to model the within-subject correlations. When using this structure you are estimating many parameters. If the numbers of subject used is small then these estimates may be unreliable, see Pinherio and Bates (2002).

Categorised case profiles plot of the observed data (on the square root scale)

Note: When comparing covariance structures, a lower AIC or BIC value indicates a better fit.

Conclusion: There are no statistically significant overall differences, at the 5% level, between the levels of any of the terms in the table of overall tests.

Tip: While it is a good idea to consider the overall tests in the above table, we should not rely on them when deciding whether or not to make pairwise comparisons.

Diagnostic plots

Residuals vs. predicted plot

Tip: On this plot look to see if the spread of the points increases as the predicted values increase. If so the response may need transforming.

Tip: Any observation with a standardised residual less than -3 or greater than 3 (SD) should be investigated as a possible outlier.

Comment: The standardised residuals are obtained by subtracting the fitted values from the responses and dividing by the estimated within-group standard error.

Normal probability plot

Tip: Check that the points lie along the dotted line. If not then the data may be non-normally distributed.

Warning: As these tests are not adjusted for multiplicity there is a risk of false positive results. Only use the pairwise comparisons you planned to make a-priori, these are the so called Planned Comparisons, see Snedecor and Cochran (1989). No options are available in this module to make multiple comparison adjustments. If you wish to apply a multiple comparison adjustment to these results then use the P-value Adjustment module.

Analysis description

The data were analysed using a 4-way repeated measures mixed model approach, with Treat 1, Treat 2 and Treat3 as treatment factors, Day 1 as the repeated factor and Block1 and Block2 as blocking factors. This was followed by Planned Comparisons on the predicted means to compare the levels of the effect Treat 1 * Treat 2 * Treat3 * Day 1. The response was square root transformed prior to analysis to stabilise the variance.

The unstructured covariance structure allowed the variability of the responses to be different, depending on the level of Day 1. This structure also allowed the correlation between responses from any pair of levels of Day 1 to be different. While this approach is the most general it should be used with care when there are few subjects, as many parameters are required to be estimated. These estimates may not be very reliable.

A full description of mixed model theory, including information on the R nlme package used by InVivoStat, can be found in Venables and Ripley (2003) and Pinherio and Bates (2002).

For more information on the theoretical approaches that are implemented within this module, see Bate and Clark (2014).
